{"type":"message","id":"2c64bcc6","parentId":"24bc49d4","timestamp":"2026-03-24T16:05:41.473Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_6iskgbbwjwml_1","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# Pulse: 2026-03-24 120507\n\n## Applied Mutations\nNo mutations applied this cycle.\nRejected: research/CFI_COMPRESSION_EXPERIMENT.md (missing)\n\n## LLM Response\n<think>\r\nLet me analyze the current state:\r\n\r\n1. Phase 0 and Phase 1 are complete\r\n2. CFI Analysis was just completed (2026-03-24) - finding that 44.8% of frequency-invariants are noise (CFI=0)\r\n3. Pending items include:\r\n   - CFI-weighted compression experiment (compare next-pulse prediction vs frequency baseline)\r\n   - Implement CFI filtering to remove metaprogramming contamination\r\n   - Distinguish \"constant format\" from \"research trajectory\"\r\n\r\nThe next logical step based on the pending items and the CFI findings would be to design and set up the CFI-weighted compression experiment. This would involve:\r\n\r\n1. Creating a comparison between frequency-only compression vs CFI-weighted compression\r\n2. Measuring prediction quality across pulses\r\n\r\nLet me create a concrete action that advances this goal. I should create a research document that outlines the CFI-weighted compression experiment design, which would then serve as the blueprint for implementation.\r\n\r\nActually, looking at the notes - the CFI results were just found. The next step from the findings is to run the CFI-weighted compression experiment. Let me create a concrete experiment design document that specifies:\r\n1. How to weight by CFI\r\n2. How to compare vs frequency baseline\r\n3. Success metrics\r\n\r\nThis is a concrete file creation that advances the goals.\r\n</think>\r\n\r\n### OBSERVATION\r\nCFI analysis revealed that 44.8% of frequency-invariants are pure noise (CFI=0), while only 5.7% are true causal anchors (CFI>=0.7). The immediate next step is to design and implement a CFI-weighted compression experiment to test whether CFI-weighting improves next-pulse prediction quality over frequency-only baseline.\r\n\r\n### ACTION\r\nCreate the CFI-weighted compression experiment design document that specifies methodology, success metrics, and implementation approach for comparing CFI-weighted vs frequency-only compression.\r\n\r\n### MUTATION\r\n`\r\nold_text: (new file)\r\nnew_text: # CFI-Weighted Compression Experiment\r\n\r\n**Created:** 2026-03-24\r\n**Status:** Ready for implementation\r\n**Priority:** HIGH - tests core hypothesis that CFI > frequency for trajectory prediction\r\n\r\n## Hypothesis\r\n\r\nCFI-weighted compression should outperform frequency-only compression for predicting the next pulse's research trajectory because:\r\n- CFI filters out metaprogramming artifacts (noise) that inflate frequency counts\r\n- CFI preserves true causal anchors (research decisions, key insights)\r\n- Frequency compresses equally toward noise and signal\r\n\r\n## Experiment Design\r\n\r\n### Setup\r\n1. Take current pulse history as corpus\r\n2. Compute invariants across all pulses using existing frequency analysis\r\n3. Apply CFI scoring to each invariant\r\n4. Compare two compression strategies on held-out pulse\r\n\r\n### Compression Strategies\r\n\r\n**Strategy A: Frequency-Only (Baseline)**\r\n```\r\nweight(invariant) = frequency(invariant) / total_tokens\r\n```\r\n\r\n**Strategy B: CFI-Weighted (Test)**\r\n```\r\nweight(invariant) = CFI(invariant) * frequency(invariant) / total_tokens\r\n```\r\n\r\n### Prediction Task\r\nGiven compressed representation of pulses 1..N, predict presence/absence of each invariant in pulse N+1.\r\n\r\n### Metrics\r\n1. **Precision@K**: Of top-K predicted invariants, what fraction appear in pulse N+1?\r\n2. **Recall@K**: Of actual invariants in pulse N+1, what fraction in top-K predictions?\r\n3. **F1@K**: Harmonic mean of precision and recall\r\n4. **Compression Ratio**: tokens(compressed) / tokens(original)\r\n\r\n### Implementation Steps\r\n1. Extract invariants from pulse_*.md files using existing frequency analysis\r\n2. Compute CFI for each invariant (using code from `research/CFI_RESULTS.md`)\r\n3. Build two separate compressed representations\r\n4. Run prediction on held-out pulse\r\n5. Compare metrics\r\n\r\n## Expected Outcome\r\n\r\n| Metric | Frequency-Only | CFI-Weighted |\r\n|--------|---------------|--------------|\r\n| Precision@10 | ~0.3 | >0.5 |\r\n| Recall@10 | ~0.4 | >0.5 |\r\n| F1@10 | ~0.35 | >0.5 |\r\n| Compression Ratio | ~0.6 | ~0.4 |\r\n\r\nIf CFI-weighted performs worse, it would indicate:\r\n- CFI is over-filtering (removing useful low-CFI signals)\r\n- Frequency captures useful patterns CFI misses\r\n- Need hybrid approach\r\n\r\n## Files Needed\r\n- `research/CFI_RESULTS.md` - for CFI scoring algorithm\r\n- `research/FREQUENCY_ANALYSIS.md` - for invariant extraction\r\n- Pulse history: `pulse_*.md` files\r\n\r\n## Success Criterion\r\n\r\nCFI-weighted F1@10 >= 1.3x Frequency-only F1@10\r\n\r\nThis validates that CFI filtering removes noise without losing predictive signal.\r\n`\r\nfile: research/CFI_COMPRESSION_EXPERIMENT.md\r\n`\n\n## For Next Instantiation\n- Proposed mutations waiting: 0\n- Completed at: 2026-03-24 12:05:36\r\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774368341471}}
